  "review": "I grew up watching Nick and Jerry with my parents on PBS.br br It is interesting to watch the two of them. They each are such accomplished actors in their own ways. Their acting styles complement each other perfectly.br br In this film, they portray two ex-CIA operatives who have retired from their careers and are living a quiet life in Maine. One, Jerry, is a writer, and Nick is a sailor. The two of them are involved in a case involving a former colleague who is kidnapped and held hostage.br br Although the kidnapping happens early in the film, it sets up the plot nicely and adds tension to the story. From there, events unfold at a steady pace, keeping the viewer interested until the conclusion.br br At its heart, however, the film is a character piece that allows the audience to view the actions of Nick and Jerry from the perspective of the two main characters. There is a lot of depth in their characters. For instance, Jerry is dealing with issues related to his past and the legacy of the CIA.br br While the film contains action sequences and violence, it also deals with themes such as redemption and forgiveness. The acting quality is excellent, including supporting players such as William Dafoe and Tom Cavanaugh. The dialogue is realistic, and the scenes often feel authentic. The film is rated PG-13 due to language and violence, although it is fairly mild compared to most films in that category. Overall, it is highly recommended."  
